# User-Level Instructions

> **Platform:** any POSIX (Linux/macOS/WSL2) | **Shell:** bash | **Node:** 20+ recommended
> Generated from `pipelinekit` install. Edit freely after install.

# Detailed rules
@~/.claude/rules/workflow.md
@~/.claude/rules/agents-worktrees.md

## Core Principles

1. **Verification First**: Run tests/build after EVERY change. Restart app if applicable. Do not mark done without passing verification.
2. **No AI Attribution**: Zero Claude/LLM references in commits, PRs, code, docs. No `Co-Authored-By`, no `Generated with`, no AI comments.
3. **Commit Only When Asked**: Wait for explicit user confirmation. Exception: worktree agents auto-commit `wip:` messages.
4. **Plan Trust**: When a plan specifies exact files, line numbers, and code changes — skip all exploration. Implement directly.
5. **Caveman Default**: Responses are terse (`wenyan-ultra`) by default with the three-zone content split — Zone 1 code/paths/commits stay normal English, Zone 2 narrative prose uses real classical Chinese 文言 (Han characters), Zone 3 fragments/status use ultra English. Full contract: `~/.claude/snippets/caveman-subagent.md`. See also `~/.claude/skills/caveman-mode/SKILL.md`, or `/caveman lite|full|ultra|wenyan|off` to adjust.
6. **Subagent-First (default)**: Dispatch any non-trivial work via the `Agent` tool by default — no trigger keyword required. The `subagent-first-nudge.sh` hook injects a default-mode reminder on every prompt. Main session orchestrates; subagents execute. Bundle multiple independent streams in a SINGLE assistant turn (multiple `Agent` calls in one message) so they run concurrently. Inline is the EXCEPTION, reserved for trivial one-shots (≤ ~3 tool calls), interactive Q&A with the user present, or per-prompt opt-out via literal phrases: `no subagents`, `no agents`, `do it inline`, `do it yourself`, `skip agents`, `no dispatch`, `don't dispatch`. Kill switch: `PIPELINE_NO_SUBAGENT_NUDGE=1`. Full protocol: `~/.claude/rules/agents-worktrees.md § Subagent Defaults`.

## Tool Usage Rules

- **Code search** (find functions, classes, patterns): Grep/Glob (native)
- **Semantic code navigation** (cross-file refs, symbol graph): `serena` MCP if configured
- **Library/framework docs** (how does X API work?): `context7` MCP resolve-library-id → query-docs
- **Structural code patterns** (class hierarchies, call graphs): `RepoMapper` MCP if configured
- **Documentation/specs/PDFs**: `local-rag` MCP query_documents if configured
- **Web research** (current events, non-cached docs): WebSearch → WebFetch
- **Symbolic code graph** (function-call traversal, identifier lookup): `codegraph` MCP if configured (pre-flight 50k-file gate via `/codegraph-init`)
- **Knowledge graph** (entity/relationship extraction from project artifacts): `graphify` MCP if configured (pre-flight 50k-file gate via `/graphify-init`)
- **Canonical memory store** (read/write project memories via MCP tools): `agentmemory` MCP — see § Memory System for the tool surface and Ebbinghaus curve detail.
- **Interactive UI / annotation surface** (visual front-end for tool / memory inspection): `Understand-Anything` plugin (NOT an MCP server — installed via the harness plugin marketplace at `scripts/install.sh` provisioning time; see [memory-graph-stack.html](memory-graph-stack.html) for the four-tool stack overview).

## Claude Code Environment Defaults

pipelinekit pins one Claude Code env var at install time via `~/.claude/settings.json`. The pin is additive: any value you set in `settings.json` before re-running install wins on collision (user-wins semantics).

**Pinned default:** `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_1M_CONTEXT=1` — disables the 1M extended-context window so prompt caching stays aligned to the 200K boundary where Anthropic's 5-minute cache TTL applies most efficiently. Documented at <https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/claude-code/model-config>.

**Where it lives:** `~/.claude/settings.json` `env` block, written by `bash scripts/install.sh` when invoked with `CLAUDE_INSTALL_SETTINGS=1`.

**Opt-out:** set `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_1M_CONTEXT=0` (or any other value) in `~/.claude/settings.json` BEFORE re-running install. pipelinekit only fills absent keys; your value survives untouched.

**Apply on an existing install:** re-run `CLAUDE_INSTALL_SETTINGS=1 bash scripts/install.sh`. Other top-level keys (`model`, `enabledPlugins`, `extraKnownMarketplaces`, etc.) are preserved across the re-run.

**Withdrawn:** `CLAUDE_CODE_AUTO_COMPACT_WINDOW=100000` was previously considered but is NOT a real Claude Code env var — it appeared in a third-party post but is not documented in the Anthropic env-var catalog (<https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/claude-code/settings>) or model-config page. Claude Code silently ignores unknown env vars, so it had no effect. The auto-compact threshold is not currently user-configurable via env var; if you need to compact early, invoke `/compact` manually.

## Memory System

Memories live in agentmemory MCP — the canonical write and read surface. The legacy flat-file store at `~/.claude/projects/<project-slug>/memory/*.md` is preserved read-only for a 30-day rollback window; cleanup of the flat-file store is a separate future feature. Do NOT write new markdown memory files unless `PIPELINE_KEEP_FLAT_FILE_MEMORY=1` is set (see § Dual-write opt-in below).

### Tool surface

The agentmemory MCP exposes four tools — use them in this order of decreasing frequency:
- `memory_save` — write one memory entry. Fields: `tags` (list of strings), `category` (one of `user|feedback|project|reference|other`), `content` (the memory body, free-form text).
- `memory_recall` — read by tags AND/OR category. Returns matching entries ranked by Ebbinghaus recency.
- `memory_smart_search` — semantic search across all memories regardless of tags. Use when tags are unknown.
- `memory_consolidate` — periodic relation-graph rebuild. Operator-invoked; not session-frequency.

### Taxonomy mapping

| Pipelinekit type (legacy) | agentmemory `tags`                                            | agentmemory `category` |
|---------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------|
| `user`                    | `[profile]`                                                   | `user`                 |
| `feedback`                | `[feedback]` + derived from `name` (e.g. `subagent-first`)    | `feedback`             |
| `project`                 | `[project, <slug>]`                                           | `project`              |
| `reference`               | `[reference]`                                                 | `reference`            |

### When NOT to save

Do not invoke `memory_save` for transient session state (active TODO trackers, intermediate scratchpads, partial command outputs), for project file contents (use `Read` against the file directly), for user PII unless the user has explicitly directed it as a saved preference, or for information already covered by an existing memory entry on the same `tags`. When in doubt, leave it unsaved — memory pollution is harder to fix than a missed save.

### Ebbinghaus curve

agentmemory computes recency-weighted relevance via an Ebbinghaus forgetting curve over `last_accessed` (not stored confidence). Recall ranking decays automatically; you do NOT need to track `last_seen` / `confidence` fields manually. See the upstream agentmemory README for the curve coefficients.

### Rollback window

The flat-file store at `~/.claude/projects/<project-slug>/memory/*.md` remains readable for 30 days following migration. Use it as a side-by-side comparison surface while validating agentmemory's behavior. Hard-deletion of the flat-file store is deferred to a separate future feature; this feature does NOT remove any markdown file.

### Dual-write opt-in

Set `PIPELINE_KEEP_FLAT_FILE_MEMORY=1` in the environment to ALSO emit a flat-file sidecar at `~/.claude/projects/<project-slug>/memory/<filename>.md` alongside each `memory_save` invocation. This is a system-prompt-level toggle (Claude's save behavior changes), NOT a hook-level toggle. The dual-write surface exists for operator-driven A/B verification during the 30-day rollback window. The sidecar filename convention (`<category>_<tags-joined-with-underscores>.md`) is documented in `documentation/memory-migration-notes.html`.

## Notifications

When `/pipeline` reaches a state requiring user attention — budget breach, error, end-of-feature, permission prompt — it emits a push notification via native Claude Code surfaces. There is no custom notification config file, no parallel rate limiter — Channels' built-in mechanics are authoritative.

### Hook event mapping

| Hook event | Notify event_type | Surface |
|------------|-------------------|---------|
| `Stop` | `feature-done` | `PushNotification` (interactive) OR `terminalSequence` (fallback) |
| `PermissionRequest` | `question` | `terminalSequence` (OSC 777) |
| `Notification` | `error` / `budget-breach` / `dropped` | `terminalSequence` (OSC 777) |
| `PreCompact` (= `PostCompact` matcher in `~/.claude/settings.json`) | `compact` | `terminalSequence` |

### Surfaces

- `PushNotification` tool (Claude Code 2.1.110+) — requires interactive session + Remote Control + "Push when Claude decides" enabled in the Claude Code mobile app.
- `Notification`-hook `terminalSequence` — JSON field returned by the hook handler; emits OSC 777 desktop notification. Non-blocking; any exit code is non-blocking by contract.
- `Channels` surface (Claude Code 2.1.121+) — for managed-org sessions; inbound delivery requires `channelsEnabled: true` in `~/.claude/settings.json`. Users opt in themselves; pipelinekit does NOT auto-enable.

### Payload (6 fields)

Notifications carry: `feature_index`, `step`, `event_type`, `text` (≤ 200 chars, truncated with ellipsis), `action_link` (deep link OR signal-file path), `feature_name`. Charter / analysis / plan / review file contents do not leak — the 200-char cap is a hard limit. Full schema in `~/.claude/skills/pipeline/reference.md § Notification payload schema`.

### Opt-out

- Set `channelsEnabled: false` in `~/.claude/settings.json` to disable inbound Channels delivery.
- Set `PIPELINE_NO_NOTIFICATIONS=1` in the environment per-run to short-circuit the helper for that run (no emit at all).

## Context Management

- Context-aware clearing between pipeline steps (see `rules/workflow.md`). `/compact` proactively around 50% capacity.
- After 2 failed corrections, `/clear` and rewrite the prompt.
- Subagents for investigation/exploration — keeps main context clean.
- Prefer direct work for coding; subagents for reading/exploring.

### Session naming

Name sessions `<project-slug>/<feature-or-task-slug>` to distinguish concurrent `/resume` entries by purpose rather than timestamp or UUID. This is advisory — no enforcement mechanism.

```bash
claude -n "myproject/feature-x"
claude -n "myproject/refactor-auth"
```

## Git

- Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `chore:`, `perf:`, `style:`, `build:`, `ci:` (enforced by `~/.claude/hooks/validate-commit-msg.sh`). No emojis.
- No `Co-authored-by` lines in commits or PR bodies.
- Claude workflow exclusions → `.git/info/exclude` (NOT `.gitignore`).
- Never stage files listed in `rules/workflow.md` § Plan & Progress → "Never stage" (canonical list). Key items: `.env`, `.claude/`, `docs/` workflow files, `credentials*`.

## Agents & Worktrees

- Named agents only when task prompt explicitly instructs.
- Worktree agents: `wip: [description]` commit before reporting done (enforced by hook).
- Squash-merge worktree branches. Clean conventional message — no `wip:`, stream names, or finding counts.
- Interactive single-stream worktrees: prefer the native `EnterWorktree` / `ExitWorktree` tools (Claude CLI `>= v2.1.72`); on older CLI builds, fall back to manual `git worktree add`. The `isolation: "worktree"` Agent-tool pattern remains the mechanism for parallel-stream dispatch.
- See `rules/agents-worktrees.md` for detailed protocol.

## Task Prompt Format

```
### Task X.Y: [Name]
> Model: [model] | Effort: [level] | Agent: [name or none] | /clear before starting
```
When a task prompt specifies a model, pass it via the Agent tool's `model` parameter.

## Verification vs. Quality Gate

- **Verification** (automatic): Run build/tests after every task.
- **Quality Gate** (opt-in): Verification + code-reviewer agent. Only when task prompt specifies.

## Workflow Pipelines

Pipelines are defined by skills. Each pipeline skill ends with a "What's Next" block — follow it. Human drives forward; Claude does not auto-advance.

Autonomous option: `/pipeline [feature-file]` — runs the full workflow per feature. Supports both **dev** items (auto-routed through TDD: `tdd-test-writer` → `tdd-implementer`) and **non-dev** items (docs, ops, chores — skip TDD). Routing is derived from the feature's commit-type prefix; override with `**Type:** dev|non-dev` in the feature block. See `~/.claude/skills/pipeline/SKILL.md` § Step 5.5 for full routing detail.

**Charter Mode (default-on):** `/pipeline` opens with a Charter Discovery phase (Step 0) that asks you 9 structured questions and writes `docs/charter.md`. Downstream phases (`/analyze`, `/create-plan`, `/implement-plan`, `/review`, `/ppr`) read the charter to scope their work automatically. Skip it with `--no-charter` for legacy autonomous behavior, or adopt an existing charter with `--charter <path>`. For full detail see `docs/pipeline.md` § Charter Mode.

See `~/.claude/rules/workflow.md` for the argument convention, base-branch detection, and context-aware clearing rules.

## Consumer Web App Workflows

The native pipelinekit toolchain ships by default and covers backend, library, data-pipeline, and CLI workloads out of the box. Consumer web app workflows are out of scope for pipelinekit's default install. `gstack` is a third-party project (`alirezarezvani/gstack`); to install it, see its own README.

## Mobile App Workflows

The mobile toolchain ships by default. `claude/agents/mobile-dev.md`, `claude/skills/ios/SKILL.md`, and `claude/skills/expo/SKILL.md` are always available. iOS-specific build steps runtime-detect Xcode (`xcrun --find` probe) and skip silently on non-macOS hosts.

## Azure Workflows

The Azure toolchain ships by default. `@azure-deployment-engineer` and the `azure-ops` skill are always available. Azure CLI auto-install runs at `scripts/install.sh` time on Debian / Ubuntu hosts; on other hosts the installer prints the Homebrew / Microsoft-docs link and continues without failure.

## Azure Mode

Per-project workflow overlay for Azure deployments. Use when a project ships to Azure (App Service, Container Apps, Function Apps, or Azure DB). Routes deployment-shaped work through `@azure-deployment-engineer` and the `azure-ops` skill; non-deployment phases continue to use the default pipeline agents.

| Phase | Agents / Skills | Notes |
|-------|-----------------|-------|
| analyze | default `/analyze` | No Azure-specific gating at analyze-time. |
| plan | default `/create-plan` | If plan touches Azure deploy config, include explicit `@azure-deployment-engineer` task per resource. |
| implement | `@azure-deployment-engineer` for ARM / Bicep / `az` CLI / pipeline YAML tasks; default agents otherwise | Use the `azure-ops` skill for day-to-day ops against an already-authenticated context. |
| review | default `/review` + `@azure-deployment-engineer` consulted on Azure-touching diffs | Security-auditor remains primary on auth / secret / RBAC changes. |
| merge | default `/ppr` | No Azure-specific merge gate. |

**Gotchas:**
- `azure-ops` STOPS and prompts if `az account show` fails — never auto-authenticates. Run `az login` (or the CI service-principal equivalent) before invoking deploy commands.
- Azure CLI auto-install runs at `scripts/install.sh` time on Debian / Ubuntu only. On macOS / RHEL / Arch hosts the installer prints the Homebrew / Microsoft-docs link and continues; install the CLI manually before first use.
- Secrets (connection strings, SAS tokens, service-principal JSON) NEVER go in committed files. Use Key Vault references in App Settings, or store under names matched by `~/.claude/config/never-stage.txt` so `block-stage-sensitive.sh` refuses to stage them.
- App Service / Container Apps deploys are not idempotent across regions — confirm the target `--resource-group` + `--name` before re-running a deploy command.

